# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aldolase-a-deficiency
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] 1,3-Bisphosphoglycerate is the conjugate base of 1,3-bisphosphoglyceric acid.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] It is phosphorylated at the number 1 and 3 carbons.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The result of this phosphorylation gives 1,3BPG important biological properties such as the ability to donate a phosphate group to adenosine diphosphate (ADP) in order to form the energy storage molecule adenosine triphosphate (ATP).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Compound C00118 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Enzyme 1.2.1.12 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Compound C00236 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Enzyme 2.7.2.3 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Compound C00197 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] 1,3BPG is a macroergic metabolic intermediate in the glycolytic pathway.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] It is created by the exergonic oxidation of the aldehyde in glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The result of this oxidation is the conversion of the aldehyde group into a carboxylic acid group which drives the formation of an acyl phosphate bond.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The latter reaction is the only step in the glycolytic pathway in which NAD+ is converted into NADH.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The formation reaction of 1,3BPG requires the presence of an enzyme called glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate dehydrogenase.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The high-energy acyl phosphate bond of 1,3BPG is important in respiration as it assists in the formation of ATP.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The molecule of ATP created during the following reaction is the first molecule produced during respiration.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The transfer of an inorganic phosphate from the carboxyl group on 1,3BPG to ADP to form ATP is reversible due to a low ΔG.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This is as a result of one acyl phosphate bond being cleaved whilst another is created.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This reaction is not naturally spontaneous and requires the presence of a catalyst.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This role is performed by the enzyme phosphoglycerate kinase.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] During the reaction phosphoglycerate kinase undergoes a substrate induced conformational change similar to another metabolic enzyme called hexokinase.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Because two molecules of glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate are formed during glycolysis from one molecule of glucose, 1,3BPG can be said to be responsible for two of the ten molecules of ATP produced during the entire process.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Glycolysis also uses two molecules of ATP in its initial stages as a committed and irreversible step.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] For this reason glycolysis is not reversible and has a net produce of 2 molecules of ATP and two of NADH.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The two molecules of NADH themselves go on to produce approximately 3 molecules of ATP each.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] 1,3-BPG has a very similar role in the Calvin cycle to its role in the glycolytic pathway.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] For this reason both reactions are said to be analogous.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] However the reaction pathway is effectively reversed.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The only other major difference between the two reactions is that NADPH is used as an electron donor in the calvin cycle whilst NAD+ is used as an electron acceptor in glycolysis.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] In this reaction cycle 1,3BPG originates from 3-phosphoglycerate and is made into glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate by the action of specific enzymes.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Contrary to the similar reactions of the glycolytic pathway, 1,3BPG in the Calvin cycle does not produce ATP but instead uses it.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] For this reason it can be considered to be an irreversible and committed step in the cycle.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The outcome of this section of the cycle is an inorganic phosphate is removed from 1,3BPG as a hydrogen ion and two electrons are added to the compound+.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] In complete reverse of the glycolytic pathway reaction, the enzyme phosphoglycerate kinase catalyses the reduction of the carboxyl group of 1,3BPG to form an aldehyde instead.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This reaction also releases an inorganic phosphate molecule which is subsequently used as energy for the donation of electrons from the conversion of NADPH to NADP+.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Overseeing this latter stage of the reaction is the enzyme glyceraldehyde-phosphate dehydrogenase.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] During normal metabolism in human erythrocytes, ≈19% of the 1,3BPG produced does not go any further in the glycolytic pathway.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] It is instead shunted through the Luebering–Rapoport pathway involving the reduction of ATP in the red blood cells.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] During this alternate pathway it is made into a similar molecule called 2,3-bisphosphoglyceric acid (2,3BPG).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] 2,3BPG is used as a mechanism to oversee the efficient release of oxygen from hemoglobin.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Levels of this 1,3BPG will raise in a patient's blood when oxygen levels are low as this is one of the mechanisms of acclimatization.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Low oxygen levels trigger a rise in 1,3BPG levels which in turn raises the level of 2,3BPG which alters the efficiency of oxygen dissociation from hemoglobin.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] D-2,3-BPG is present in human red blood cells (RBC; erythrocyte) at approximately 5 mmol/L.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] It interacts with deoxygenated hemoglobin beta subunits and decreases the affinity for oxygen and allosterically promotes the release of the remaining oxygen molecules bound to the hemoglobin.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Therefore, it enhances the ability of RBCs to release oxygen near tissues that need it most.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Its function was discovered in 1967 by Reinhold Benesch and Ruth Benesch.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] 2,3-BPG is formed from 1,3-BPG by the enzyme BPG mutase.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] It can then be broken down by 2,3-BPG phosphatase to form 3-phosphoglycerate.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Its synthesis and breakdown are, therefore, a way around a step of glycolysis, with the net expense of one ATP per molecule of 2,3-BPG generated as the high-energy carboxylic acid-phosphate mixed anhydride bond is cleaved by 2,3-BPG phosphatase.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] 2,3-BPG, the most concentrated organophosphate in the erythrocyte, forms 3-PG by the action of bisphosphoglycerate phosphatase.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The concentration of 2,3-BPG varies proportionately to the [H+].
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] There is a delicate balance between the need to generate ATP to support energy requirements for cell metabolism and the need to maintain appropriate oxygenation/deoxygenation status of hemoglobin.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This balance is maintained by isomerisation of 1,3-BPG to 2,3-BPG, which enhances the deoxygenation of hemoglobin.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] When 2,3-BPG binds to deoxyhemoglobin, it acts to stabilize the low oxygen affinity state (T state) of the oxygen carrier.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] It fits neatly into the cavity of the deoxy- conformation, exploiting the molecular symmetry and positive polarity by forming salt bridges with lysine and histidine residues in the β subunits of hemoglobin.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The R state, with oxygen bound to a heme group, has a different conformation and does not allow this interaction.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] By itself, hemoglobin has sigmoid-like kinetics.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] In selectively binding to deoxyhemoglobin, 2,3-BPG stabilizes the T state conformation, making it harder for oxygen to bind hemoglobin and more likely to be released to adjacent tissues.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] An increase in 2,3-BPG essentially facilitates the delivery of oxygen from hemoglobin in target tissues, at a cost of also making it somewhat more difficult for hemoglobin to take up oxygen in the lungs.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This mechanism makes maternal-fetal oxygenation more efficient, as fetal 2,3-BPG is lower than maternal levels, resulting in a higher uptake of oxygen by the fetal blood in the placenta.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] 2,3-BPG may also serve to physiologically counteract certain metabolic disturbances to the oxygen-hemoglobin dissociation curve.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] For example, at high altitudes, low atmospheric oxygen content can cause hyperventilation and resultant metabolic alkalosis which causes an abnormal left-shift of the oxygen-hemoglobin dissociation curve, and this can be counteracted by an increase in 2,3-BPG.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] In pregnant women, there is a 30% increase in intracellular 2,3-BPG.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This lowers the maternal hemoglobin affinity for oxygen, and therefore allows more oxygen to be offloaded to the fetus in the maternal uterine arteries.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The fetus has a low sensitivity to 2,3-BPG, so its hemoglobin has a higher affinity for oxygen.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Therefore, although the pO2 in the uterine arteries is low, the fetal umbilical artery (which carries deoxygenated blood) can still get oxygenated from them.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The increased maternal 2,3-BPG also causes a decreased affinity for oxygen takeup in the lungs, but this is usually compensated by a physiologic increased respiratory rate in pregnancy.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Fetal hemoglobin (HbF), on the other hand, exhibits a low affinity for 2,3-BPG, resulting in a higher binding affinity for oxygen.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This increased oxygen-binding affinity relative to that of adult hemoglobin (HbA) is due to HbF's having two α/γ dimers as opposed to the two α/β dimers of HbA.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The positive histidine residues of HbA β-subunits that are essential for forming the 2,3-BPG binding pocket are replaced by serine residues in HbF γ-subunits.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Like that, histidine nº143 gets lost, so 2,3-BPG has difficulties in linking to the fetal hemoglobin, and it looks like the pure hemoglobin.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Increased binding affinity of fetal hemoglobin relative to HbA facilitates the passage of oxygen across the placental membrane from the mother to the fetus.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] A 2004 study checked the effects of thyroid hormone on 2,3-BPG levels.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The result was that the hyperthyroidism modulates in vivo 2,3-BPG content in erythrocytes by changes in the expression of phosphoglycerate mutase (PGM) and 2,3-BPG synthase.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This result shows that the increase in the 2,3-BPG content of erythrocytes observed in hyperthyroidism doesn’t depend on any variation in the rate of circulating hemoglobin, but seems to be a direct consequence of the stimulating effect of thyroid hormones on erythrocyte glycolytic activity.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Red cells increase their intracellular 2,3-BPG concentration as much as five times within one to two hours in patients with chronic anemia, when the oxygen carrying capacity of the blood is diminished.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This results in a rightward shift of the oxygen dissociation curve and more oxygen being released to the tissues.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Increased 2,3-BPG levels have been noted in individuals with chronic hypoxia, and chronic lung disease.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] An association between low amounts of 2,3-BPG and the occurrence of high altitude pulmonary edema at high altitudes has been observed.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] In a 1998 study, erythrocyte 2,3-BPG concentration was analyzed during the hemodialysis process.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The 2,3-BPG concentration was expressed relative to the hemoglobin tetramer (Hb4) concentration as the 2,3-BPG/Hb4 ratio.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Physiologically, an increase in 2,3-BPG levels would be expected to counteract the hypoxia that is frequently observed in this process.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Nevertheless, the results show a 2,3-BPG/Hb4 ratio decreased.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This is due to the procedure itself: mechanical stress on the erythrocytes is believed to cause the 2,3-BPG escape, which is then removed by hemodialysis.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The concentrations of calcium, phosphate, creatinine, urea and albumin did not correlate significantly with the total change in 2,3-BPG/Hb4 ratio.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] However, the ratio sampled just before dialysis correlated significantly and positively with the total weekly dosage of erythropoietin (main hormone in erythrocyte formation) given to the patients.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/2-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Storage of transfusable blood in a blood bank reduces 2,3-BPG.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] Many patients with 6-phosphogluconate dehydrogenase deficiency are carriers and have no symptoms.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] It has been discovered that symptoms manifest more frequently in female carriers.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] Depending on how severe the deficiency is, it has been demonstrated that enzyme activity is reduced by 35–65%.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] 6PGD deficiency is a recessive hereditary disorder located on the P arm of chromosome 1.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] It is an autosomal disease, not associated with the sex chromosomes and can affect both sexes.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] The lack of synthesis of a specific protein on chromosome 1 has reduced a subject suffering from 6PGD deficiency from producing adequate amounts of the 6-phosphogluconate dehydrogenase enzyme.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] Transfer of the disease can be passed from a parent, even when the parent is asymptomatic.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] 6-Phosphogluconate dehydrogenase (6PGD) is an enzyme in the pentose phosphate pathway (see image).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] 6PGD catalyzes the reaction of 6-phosphogluconate to an unstable form of 3-keto-6-phosphogluconate, and yields a co-enzyme nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide phosphate (NADPH) as a byproduct.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] The reaction is the second NADPH releasing reaction in the pentose phosphate pathway, the first being catalyzed by glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] 3-keto-6-phosphogluconate then rapidly (in an irreversible reaction) decarboxylates to CO2 and ribulose-5-phosphate, which is the precursor to many vital metabolic processes.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] The NADPH pathway (both 6PGD and G6PD reactions) is the only source of reductant to reduce glutathione in red blood cells.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] The role of erythrocytes as oxygen carriers puts them at risk of being damaged by oxidizing free radicals.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] The reduction of glutathione acts as an antioxidant and prevents damage from reactive oxygen species.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] People suffering from 6PGD or G6PD deficiency (or both) are at risk of hemolytic anemia in states of oxidative stress.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] Oxidative stress can result from infection and from chemical exposure to medication and certain foods.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] Broad beans, e.g., fava beans, contain high levels of vicine, divicine, convicine and isouramil, all of which are oxidants.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] When all remaining reduced glutathione is consumed, enzymes and other proteins, such as hemoglobin are subsequently damaged by the free radicals, leading to electrolyte imbalance, cross-bonding and protein deposition in the red cell membranes.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] Damaged red cells are phagocytosed and sequestered (taken out of circulation) in the spleen.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] The hemoglobin is metabolized to bilirubin (causing jaundice).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] The red blood cells rarely disintegrate in the circulation, so hemoglobin is rarely excreted directly by the kidney, but this can occur in severe cases, causing acute kidney injury.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] The most important measure taken for treatment of 6-phosphoglucanate dehydrogenase is prevention.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] Avoidance of chemical exposures to drugs and foods that have the potential to cause hemolysis.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] Although some foods and supplements have antioxidant properties, their use does not decrease the severity of G6PD deficiency.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] Diagnosis is difficult during haemolytic episodes since reticulocytes have increased levels of enzymes and may produce erroneously normal results.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] Testing can be useful after a steady state is reached (about six weeks after the most recent episode of haemolysis), including a G6PD assay to confirm a diagnosis and G6PD spectrophotometry to detect the level of activity.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] Vaccinations against some common pathogens (e.g. hepatitis A and hepatitis B) may prevent infection-induced attacks.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] In the acute phase of hemolysis, blood transfusions might be necessary, or even dialysis in acute kidney injury.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/6-phosphogluconate-dehydrogenase-deficiency] Blood transfusion is an important symptomatic measure, as the transfused red cells are generally not 6PGD deficient and will live a normal lifespan in the recipient's circulation.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] When consumed in a metabolic process, ATP converts either to adenosine diphosphate (ADP) or to adenosine monophosphate (AMP).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Other processes, such as oxidative phosphorylation or substrate-level phosphorylation, regenerate ATP.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is also a precursor to DNA and RNA, and is used as a coenzyme.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Daily, an average adult human recycles through synthesis and hydrolysis around 50 kilograms of ATP (about 100 moles).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] From the perspective of biochemistry, ATP is classified as a nucleoside triphosphate, which indicates that it consists of three components: a nitrogenous base (adenine), the sugar ribose, and the triphosphate.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP consists of three parts: a sugar, an amine base, and a phosphate group.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] More specifically, ATP consists of an adenine attached by the #9-nitrogen atom to the 1′ carbon atom of a sugar (ribose), which in turn is attached at the 5' carbon atom of the sugar to a triphosphate group.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] In its many reactions related to metabolism, the adenine and sugar groups remain unchanged, but the triphosphate is converted to di- and monophosphate, giving respectively the derivatives ADP and AMP.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The three phosphoryl groups are labeled as alpha (α), beta (β), and, for the terminal phosphate, gamma (γ).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] In neutral solution, ionized ATP exists mostly as ATP4−, with a small proportion of ATP3−.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Polyanionic and featuring a potentially chelating polyphosphate group, ATP binds metal cations with high affinity.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The binding constant for Mg2+ is (9554).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The binding of a divalent cation, almost always magnesium, strongly affects the interaction of ATP with various proteins.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Due to the strength of the ATP-Mg2+ interaction, ATP exists in the cell mostly as a complex with Mg2+ bonded to the phosphate oxygen centers.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] A second magnesium ion is critical for ATP binding in the kinase domain.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The presence of Mg2+ regulates kinase activity.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] It is interesting from an RNA world perspective that ATP can carry a Mg2+ ion which catalyzes RNA polymerization.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Salts of ATP can be isolated as colorless solids.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is stable in aqueous solutions between pH 6.8 and 7.4 (in the absence of catalysts).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] At more extreme pH levels, it rapidly hydrolyses to ADP and phosphate.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Living cells maintain the ratio of ATP to ADP at a point ten orders of magnitude from equilibrium, with ATP concentrations fivefold higher than the concentration of ADP.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] In the context of biochemical reactions, the P-O-P bonds are frequently referred to as *high-energy bonds*.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] releases Δ*G*°' = −30.5 kJ/mol (−7.3 kcal/mol) of Gibbs free energy under standard conditions when all metabolite concentrations are 1 mol/L.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] This may differ under physiological conditions if the reactant and products are not exactly in these ionization states.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] At cytoplasmic conditions, where the ADP/ATP ratio is 10 orders of magnitude from equilibrium, the Δ*G* is around −57 kJ/mol.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Along with pH, the free energy change of ATP hydrolysis is also associated with Mg2+ concentration, from ΔG°' = −35.7 kJ/mol at a Mg2+ concentration of zero, to ΔG°' = −31 kJ/mol at [Mg2+] = 5 mM.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Higher concentrations of Mg2+ decrease free energy released in the reaction due to binding of Mg2+ ions to negatively charged oxygen atoms of ATP at pH 7.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] A typical intracellular concentration of ATP is 1–10 μmol per gram of muscle tissue in a variety of eukaryotes.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The dephosphorylation of ATP and rephosphorylation of ADP and AMP occur repeatedly in the course of aerobic metabolism.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP can be produced by a number of distinct cellular processes; the three main pathways in eukaryotes are (1) glycolysis, (2) the citric acid cycle/oxidative phosphorylation, and (3) beta-oxidation.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The overall process of oxidizing glucose to carbon dioxide, the combination of pathways 1 and 2, known as cellular respiration, produces about 30 equivalents of ATP from each molecule of glucose.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP production by a non-photosynthetic aerobic eukaryote occurs mainly in the mitochondria, which comprise nearly 25% of the volume of a typical cell.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] In glycolysis, glucose and glycerol are metabolized to pyruvate.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis generates two equivalents of ATP through substrate phosphorylation catalyzed by two enzymes, phosphoglycerate kinase (PGK) and pyruvate kinase.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Two equivalents of nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NADH) are also produced, which can be oxidized via the electron transport chain and result in the generation of additional ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The pyruvate generated as an end-product of glycolysis is a substrate for the citric acid cycle.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis is viewed as consisting of two phases with five steps each.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] In phase 1, "the preparatory phase", glucose is converted to 2 d-glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate (g3p).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] One ATP is invested in Step 1, and another ATP is invested in Step 3.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Steps 1 and 3 of glycolysis are referred to as "Priming Steps".
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] In Phase 2, two equivalents of g3p are converted to two pyruvates.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Also, in Step 10, two further equivalents of ATP are produced.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] In Steps 7 and 10, ATP is generated from ADP.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] A net of two ATPs is formed in the glycolysis cycle.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The glycolysis pathway is later associated with the Citric Acid Cycle, which produces additional equivalents of ATP.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis is regulated allosterically by a number of metabolic compounds.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] For example, hexokinase is directly inhibited by its product, glucose-6-phosphate, and pyruvate kinase is inhibited by ATP itself.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The main control point for the glycolytic pathway is phosphofructokinase 1 (PFK1), which is allosterically inhibited by high concentrations of ATP and activated by high concentrations of AMP.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The inhibition of PFK1 by ATP is unusual since ATP is also a substrate in the reaction catalyzed by PFK1.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The active form of PFK1 enzyme is a tetramer that exists in two conformations, only one of which binds the second substrate fructose-6-phosphate (F6P).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The PFK1 enzyme has two binding sites for ATP – the active site is accessible in either protein conformation, but ATP binding to the inhibitor site stabilizes the conformation that binds F6P poorly.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] A number of other small molecules can compensate for the ATP-induced shift in equilibrium conformation and reactivate PFK1, including cyclic AMP, ammonium ions, inorganic phosphate, fructose 1,6-bisphosphate and fructose 2,6-bisphosphate.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] In the mitochondrion, pyruvate is oxidized by the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex to the acetyl group, which is fully oxidized to carbon dioxide by the citric acid cycle.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] NADH and FADH2 are recycled (to NAD+ and FAD, respectively) by oxidative phosphorylation, generating additional ATP.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The oxidation of NADH results in the synthesis of 2–3 equivalents of ATP, and the oxidation of one FADH2 yields between 1–2 equivalents of ATP.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The majority of cellular ATP is generated by this process.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Although the citric acid cycle itself does not involve molecular oxygen, it is an obligately aerobic process because O2 is used to recycle the NADH and FADH2.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] In the absence of oxygen, the citric acid cycle ceases.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The generation of ATP by the mitochondrion from cytosolic NADH relies on the malate-aspartate shuttle (and to a lesser extent, the glycerol-phosphate shuttle) because the inner mitochondrial membrane is impermeable to NADH and NAD+.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Instead of transferring the generated NADH, a malate dehydrogenase enzyme converts oxaloacetate to malate, which is translocated to the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Another malate dehydrogenase-catalyzed reaction occurs in the opposite direction, producing oxaloacetate and NADH from the newly transported malate and the mitochondrion's interior store of NAD+.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] A transaminase converts the oxaloacetate to aspartate for transport back across the membrane and into the intermembrane space.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] In oxidative phosphorylation, the passage of electrons from NADH and FADH2 through the electron transport chain releases the energy to pump protons out of the mitochondrial matrix and into the intermembrane space.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] This pumping generates a proton motive force that is the net effect of a pH gradient and an electric potential gradient across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Flow of protons down this potential gradient – that is, from the intermembrane space to the matrix – yields ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Most of the ATP synthesized in the mitochondria will be used for cellular processes in the cytosol; thus it must be exported from its site of synthesis in the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP outward movement is favored by the inner mitochondrial membrane's electrochemical potential because the cytosol has a relatively positive charge compared to the relatively negative matrix.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] For every ATP transported out, it costs 1 H+.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Therefore, making and exporting one ATP requires 4H+.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The inner membrane contains an antiporter, the ADP/ATP translocase, which is an integral membrane protein used to exchange newly synthesized ATP in the matrix for ADP in the intermembrane space.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The citric acid cycle is regulated mainly by the availability of key substrates, particularly the ratio of NAD+ to NADH and the concentrations of calcium, inorganic phosphate, ATP, ADP, and AMP.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Citrate – the ion that gives its name to the cycle – is a feedback inhibitor of citrate synthase and also inhibits PFK, providing a direct link between the regulation of the citric acid cycle and glycolysis.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] In the presence of air and various cofactors and enzymes, fatty acids are converted to acetyl-CoA.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Each cycle of beta-oxidation shortens the fatty acid chain by two carbon atoms and produces one equivalent each of acetyl-CoA, NADH, and FADH2.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The acetyl-CoA is metabolized by the citric acid cycle to generate ATP, while the NADH and FADH2 are used by oxidative phosphorylation to generate ATP.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Dozens of ATP equivalents are generated by the beta-oxidation of a single long acyl chain.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] In oxidative phosphorylation, the key control point is the reaction catalyzed by cytochrome c oxidase, which is regulated by the availability of its substrate – the reduced form of cytochrome c.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Thus, a high ratio of [NADH] to [NAD+] or a high ratio of [ADP] [Pi] to [ATP] imply a high amount of reduced cytochrome c and a high level of cytochrome c oxidase activity.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] An additional level of regulation is introduced by the transport rates of ATP and NADH between the mitochondrial matrix and the cytoplasm.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies can be used as fuels, yielding 22 ATP and 2 GTP molecules per acetoacetate molecule when oxidized in the mitochondria.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies are transported from the liver to other tissues, where acetoacetate and *beta*-hydroxybutyrate can be reconverted to acetyl-CoA to produce reducing equivalents (NADH and FADH2), via the citric acid cycle.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies cannot be used as fuel by the liver, because the liver lacks the enzyme β-ketoacyl-CoA transferase, also called thiolase.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetoacetate in low concentrations is taken up by the liver and undergoes detoxification through the methylglyoxal pathway which ends with lactate.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetoacetate in high concentrations is absorbed by cells other than those in the liver and enters a different pathway via 1,2-propanediol.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Though the pathway follows a different series of steps requiring ATP, 1,2-propanediol can be turned into pyruvate.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Fermentation is the metabolism of organic compounds in the absence of air.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] It involves substrate-level phosphorylation in the absence of a respiratory electron transport chain.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Anaerobic respiration is respiration in the absence of O2.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Prokaryotes can utilize a variety of electron acceptors.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] These include nitrate, sulfate, and carbon dioxide.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] In anaerobic organisms and prokaryotes, different pathways result in ATP.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is produced in the chloroplasts of green plants in a process similar to oxidative phosphorylation, called photophosphorylation.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP can also be synthesized through several so-called "replenishment" reactions catalyzed by the enzyme families of nucleoside diphosphate kinases (NDKs), which use other nucleoside triphosphates as a high-energy phosphate donor, and the ATP:guanido-phosphotransferase family.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] In plants, ATP is synthesized in the thylakoid membrane of the chloroplast.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The process is called photophosphorylation.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The "machinery" is similar to that in mitochondria except that light energy is used to pump protons across a membrane to produce a proton-motive force.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP synthase then ensues exactly as in oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Some of the ATP produced in the chloroplasts is consumed in the Calvin cycle, which produces triose sugars.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The total quantity of ATP in the human body is about 0.1 mol/L.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The majority of ATP is recycled from ADP by the aforementioned processes.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Thus, at any given time, the total amount of ATP + ADP remains fairly constant.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The energy used by human cells in an adult requires the hydrolysis of 100 to 150 mol/L of ATP daily, which means a human will typically use their body weight worth of ATP over the course of the day.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Each equivalent of ATP is recycled 1000–1500 times during a single day (150 / 0.1 = 1500), at approximately 9×1020 molecules/s.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The conversion of ATP to ADP is the principal mechanism for energy supply in biological processes.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] However, removing a phosphate group from ADP to produce adenosine monophosphate (AMP) also produces extra energy.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is involved in signal transduction by serving as substrate for kinases, enzymes that transfer phosphate groups.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Kinases are the most common ATP-binding proteins.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] They share a small number of common folds.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Phosphorylation of a protein by a kinase can activate a cascade such as the mitogen-activated protein kinase cascade.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is also a substrate of adenylate cyclase, most commonly in G protein-coupled receptor signal transduction pathways and is transformed to second messenger, cyclic AMP, which is involved in triggering calcium signals by the release of calcium from intracellular stores.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] This form of signal transduction is particularly important in brain function, although it is involved in the regulation of a multitude of other cellular processes.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is one of four monomers required in the synthesis of RNA.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The process is promoted by RNA polymerases.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] A similar process occurs in the formation of DNA, except that ATP is first converted to the deoxyribonucleotide dATP.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Like many condensation reactions in nature, DNA replication and DNA transcription also consume ATP.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase enzymes consume ATP in the attachment tRNA to amino acids, forming aminoacyl-tRNA complexes.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Aminoacyl transferase binds AMP-amino acid to tRNA.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The amino acid is coupled to the penultimate nucleotide at the 3′-end of the tRNA (the A in the sequence CCA) via an ester bond (roll over in illustration).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Transporting chemicals out of a cell against a gradient is often associated with ATP hydrolysis.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Transport is mediated by ATP binding cassette transporters.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The human genome encodes 48 ABC transporters, that are used for exporting drugs, lipids, and other compounds.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Cells secrete ATP to communicate with other cells in a process called purinergic signalling.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP serves as a neurotransmitter in many parts of the nervous system, modulates ciliary beating, affects vascular oxygen supply etc.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is either secreted directly across the cell membrane through channel proteins or is pumped into vesicles which then fuse with the membrane.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Cells detect ATP using the purinergic receptor proteins P2X and P2Y.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP has been shown to be a critically important signalling molecule for microglia - neuron interactions in the adult brain, as well as during brain development.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Furthermore, tissue-injury induced ATP-signalling is a major factor in rapid microglial phenotype changes.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Muscle contractions are regulated by signaling pathways, although different muscle types being regulated by specific pathways and stimuli based on their particular function.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] However, in all muscle types, contraction is performed by the proteins actin and myosin.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] When ATPase hydrolyzes the bound ATP into ADP and inorganic phosphate, myosin is positioned in a way that it can bind to actin.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Myosin bound by ADP and Pi forms cross-bridges with actin and the subsequent release of ADP and Pi releases energy as the power stroke.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The power stroke causes actin filament to slide past the myosin filament, shortening the muscle and causing a contraction.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Another ATP molecule can then bind to myosin, releasing it from actin and allowing this process to repeat.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP has recently been proposed to act as a biological hydrotrope and has been shown to affect proteome-wide solubility.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetyl phosphate (AcP), a precursor to ATP, can readily be synthesized at modest yields from thioacetate in pH 7 and 20 °C and pH 8 and 50 °C, although acetyl phosphate is less stable in warmer temperatures and alkaline conditions than in cooler and acidic to neutral conditions.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] It is unable to promote polymerization of ribonucleotides and amino acids and was only capable of phosphorylation of organic compounds.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] It was shown that it can promote aggregation and stabilization of AMP in the presence of Na+, aggregation of nucleotides could promote polymerization above 75 °C in the absence of Na+.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] It is possible that polymerization promoted by AcP could occur at mineral surfaces.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] It was shown that ADP can only be phosphorylated to ATP by AcP and other nucleoside triphosphates were not phosphorylated by AcP.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] This might explain why all lifeforms use ATP to drive biochemical reactions.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Biochemistry laboratories often use *in vitro* studies to explore ATP-dependent molecular processes.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP analogs are also used in X-ray crystallography to determine a protein structure in complex with ATP, often together with other substrates.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Enzyme inhibitors of ATP-dependent enzymes such as kinases are needed to examine the binding sites and transition states involved in ATP-dependent reactions.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Most useful ATP analogs cannot be hydrolyzed as ATP would be; instead, they trap the enzyme in a structure closely related to the ATP-bound state.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Adenosine 5′-(γ-thiotriphosphate) is an extremely common ATP analog in which one of the gamma-phosphate oxygens is replaced by a sulfur atom; this anion is hydrolyzed at a dramatically slower rate than ATP itself and functions as an inhibitor of ATP-dependent processes.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] In crystallographic studies, hydrolysis transition states are modeled by the bound vanadate ion.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Caution is warranted in interpreting the results of experiments using ATP analogs, since some enzymes can hydrolyze them at appreciable rates at high concentration.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is used intravenously for some heart-related conditions.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP was discovered in 1929 from muscle tissue by Karl Lohmann and Jendrassik and, independently, by Cyrus Fiske and Yellapragada Subba Rao of Harvard Medical School, both teams competing against each other to find an assay for phosphorus.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] It was proposed to be the intermediary between energy-yielding and energy-requiring reactions in cells by Fritz Albert Lipmann in 1941.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] He played a major role in establishing that ATP is the energy currency of a cell.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] It was first synthesized in the laboratory by Alexander Todd in 1948, and he was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1957 partly for this work.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The 1978 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to Peter Dennis Mitchell for the discovery of the chemiosmotic mechanism of ATP synthesis.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] The 1997 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was divided, one half jointly to Paul D.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adenosine-triphosphate] Walker "for their elucidation of the enzymatic mechanism underlying the synthesis of adenosine triphosphate (ATP)" and the other half to Jens C.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] A person inherits loss-of-function mutations in the *GBE1* gene from each parent, and the lack of glycogen branching enzyme (the protein encoded by *GBE1*) leads to the buildup of unbranched glycogen in cells, which harms neurons more than other kinds of cells.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] The condition is diagnosed by gathering symptoms, a neurological examination, laboratory tests including genetic testing, and medical imaging.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] As of 2025, there is no cure or treatment, but the symptoms can be managed.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] People diagnosed with APBD can live a long time after diagnosis, but will probably die earlier than people without the condition.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Adult polyglucosan body disease is a condition that affects the nervous system.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] People with this condition have problems walking due to reduced sensation in their legs (peripheral neuropathy) and progressive muscle weakness and stiffness (spasticity).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Damage to the nerves that control bladder function (neurogenic bladder) causes progressive difficulty in controlling the flow of urine.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] About half of people with adult polyglucosan body disease experience dementia.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Most people with the condition first complain of bladder issues.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] People with adult polyglucosan body disease typically first experience signs and symptoms related to the condition between ages 30 and 60.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] APBD is an autosomal recessive disorder that is caused when a person inherits genes from both parents containing one or more loss-of-function mutations in the gene *GBE1* which encodes for glycogen branching enzyme, also called 1,4-alpha-glucan-branching enzyme.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] According to reports, the most common disease-causing (pathogenic) variant of *GBE1* that is associated with APBD, particularly among those of Ashkenazi Jewish descent, is the p.Tyr329Ser (c.986A>C) mutation.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] The *GBE1* gene provides instructions for making the glycogen branching enzyme.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] This enzyme is involved in the production of a complex sugar called glycogen, which is a major source of stored energy in the body.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Most *GBE1* gene mutations result in a shortage (deficiency) of the glycogen branching enzyme, which leads to the production of abnormal glycogen molecules. called polyglucosan.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Unlike normal glycogen, polyglucosan is made up of long, unbranched chains of glucose molecules.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] The lack of glycogen branching, which is controlled by the glycogen branching enzyme, makes the polyglucosan insoluble and difficult for the cell to metabolize.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] This results in the accumulation and aggregation of polyglucosan in the cell, forming polyglucosan bodies and causing cellular damage.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Neurons appear to be particularly vulnerable to the accumulation of polyglucosan bodies in people with this disorder, leading to impaired neuronal function.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Polyglucosan can accumulate in other organs of the body; in children with GSD IV, polyglucosan accumulation can damage the liver, skeletal muscles, and heart.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Some mutations in the *GBE1* gene that cause adult polyglucosan body disease do not result in a shortage of glycogen branching enzyme.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] In people with these mutations, the activity of this enzyme is normal.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] How mutations cause the disease in these individuals is unclear.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Other people with adult polyglucosan body disease do not have identified mutations in the *GBE1* gene.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] In these individuals, the cause of the disease is unknown.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Along with evaluation of the symptoms and a neurological examination, a diagnosis can be made based on genetic testing.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Whether or not a person is making sufficient amounts of functional glycogen branching enzyme can be determined by taking a skin biopsy and testing for activity of the enzyme.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Examination of tissue biopsied from the sural nerve under a microscope can reveal the presence of polyglucosan bodies.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] There will also be white matter changes visible in a magnetic resonance imaging scans.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Adult polyglucosan body disease is an orphan disease and a glycogen storage disorder that is caused by an inborn error of metabolism, that affects the central and peripheral nervous systems.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] The condition in newborns and children caused by the same mutations is called glycogen storage disease type IV (GSD IV).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] APBD can only be prevented if parents undergo genetic screening to understand their risk of producing a child with the condition; if in vitro fertilization is used, then preimplantation genetic diagnosis can be done to identify fertilized eggs that do not carry two copies of mutated *GBE1*.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] As of 2024, there is no cure for APBD; instead symptoms are managed.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] There are various approaches to managing neurogenic bladder dysfunction, physical therapy and mobility aids to help with walking, and dementia can be managed with occupational therapy, counseling and drugs.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] The rate of progression varies significantly from person to person.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] There is not good data on outcomes; it appears that APBD likely leads to earlier death, but people with APBD can live many years after diagnosis with relatively good quality of life.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] The exact prevalence of APBD is unknown.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] As of 2025, global prevalence estimates from the Rare Genomes Project suggest that there are approximately 34,000 people worldwide with *GBE1*-related diseases (APBD and GSD IV).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] In addition, APBD and *GBE1* mutations are most prevalent in individuals of Ashkenazi Jewish heritage (approximately 1/16,000).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] However, only about 160 cases of APBD had been reported in the medical literature as of 2020.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Historically, APBD and GSD IV have been classified as discrete diseases.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] However, detailed natural history and genome analysis studies have identified overlap in GBE1 gene mutations, as well as pathogenesis, between APBD and the GSD type IV variants.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] Gregory Weiss, a person with APBD, created the Adult Polyglucosan Body Disease Research Foundation to fund research into the disease and its management.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease] In 2015 the first transgenic mouse that appeared to be a useful model organism for studying APBD was published.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] The low incidence of this syndrome is often related to aldolase A's essential glycolytic role along with its exclusive expression in blood and skeletal muscle.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Early developmental reliance and constitutive function prevents severe mutation in successful embryos.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Infrequent documentation thus prevents clear generalisation of symptoms and causes.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] However five cases have been well described.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] ALDOA deficiency is diagnosed through reduced aldoA enzymatic activity, however, both physiological response and fundamental causes vary.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Blood-related pathology is seen in all patients.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Typically diagnosed at birth, congenital nonspherocytic hemolytic anemia is characterised by premature destruction of red blood cells without apparent abnormality in shape.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] This shortened erythrocyte life-span and increased destruction links to hyperbilirubinemia which often presents as jaundice in the accumulation of bilirubin through excessive hemoglobin breakdown.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Another side effect of cellular rupture both in the form of hemolysis and rabdomyolysis is excessive plasma concentrations of electrolytes such as potassium.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] This can lead to hyperkalemia, potentially of great cardiac concern.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Glycolysis also produces 2,3-diphosphoglycerate required to modulate hemoglobin's affinity for oxygen (2,3-bisphosphoglycerate synthesis).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Thus dysregulation of glycolysis is also implicated in the functional distribution of oxygen possibly leading to organ hypoxia.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] A complex pattern for this metabolite is suggested with discrepancy in findings.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] One Japanese patient had elevated levels, while the original Jewish Canadian boy had below average concentration.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Glucose metabolism also links intrinsically to the pentose phosphate pathway in the generation of reduced nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide phosphate (NADPH) necessary for synthetic processes and reduced glutathione involved in protecting red cells against oxidant damage.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] In particular increased fructose-1,6-bisphosphate accumulation can have inhibitory effects on glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase, an essential enzyme of this pathway.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Lactate accumulation has also been noted in some patients, potentially linked to reciprocal stimulation of pyruvate kinase, a key enzyme in lactic acid fermentation.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] In non-contiguous patients an aggravated form of aldolase A deficiency has been seen to manifest in myopathy (muscular deterioration).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] This is often recognized initially through signs of muscle weakness and exercise intolerance, suggesting rapid muscular fatigue and damage, likely directly related to ATP depletion.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] This breakdown of muscular fibers, or rhabdomyolysis, can lead to detectable blood creatine phosphate level elevation and potentially exaggerated hyperkalemia.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Delayed growth and development was noted in some patients, although not fully explained, this may be generally associated with the physiological difficulties implicit in errors of energy metabolism.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] In particular neurological impairment was conjecturally linked with the predominant role of aldolase A in the brain during development.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] However, this was not substantiated with direct enzymatic kinetic study.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Elevated liver glycogen in one patent was rationalised through an accumulation of fructose-1,6-bisphosphate leading to impaired glucose metabolism and increased diversion of hexose sugars from peripheral tissues.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Within the liver the aldolase C isoform is unaffected and therefore hepatic metabolism is assumed to be normally functioning and compensatory processes may be operating.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Compromised immunity has also been indicated, relating to the predominance or exclusivity of aldolase A in leukocytes.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] This was correlated with recurrent infection in the Sicilian case.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Focal disruption of vital energy metabolism has thus far prevented complete investigation of non-catalytic perturbation.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] However relation to membrane structural stability has been implicated in the concurrence of aldolase A deficiency and dominant (mild) hereditary elliptocytosis, speculatively also relating to ATP depletion.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Characterised as a recessive disorder, symptomatic presentation requires the inheritance of aldolase A mutations from both parents.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] This conclusion is substantiated through the continuum type presentation witnessed, wherein heterozygous parents have intermediate enzyme activity.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Structural instability has been indicated in four of the patients, with particular sensitivity to increased temperature according to direct enzymatic testing.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] This is exemplified in the early diagnosis of hereditary pyropoikilocytosis in the Sicilian girl.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Deterioration with fever is likewise congruent.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] However, this direct relation has been disputed due to the increased overall metabolism and oxygen consumption also accompanying such maladies.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Sequence analysis has been conducted for three of the patients each revealing a distinct alteration at regions of typically high conservation.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] The conversion of the 128th aspartic acid to glycine causes conformational change according to CD spectral analysis and thermal lability in mutagenic analysis.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Similarly the charge disruption created through the exchange of the negatively charged glutamic acid for positively charged lysine (at residue 209 of the E helix) disrupts interface interaction of the protein's subunits and therein destabilises its native tetrahedral configuration.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] The final case is unique in its non-homozygosity.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] A comparable maternal missense mutation wherein tyrosine is replaced by cysteine alters the carboxy-terminus due to its proximity to a crucial hinge structure.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] However, the paternal nonsense mutation at arginine 303 truncates the peptide.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] It is notable that Arg303 is required for enzymatic activity.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] The initial 1973 case is atypical, in that no indication of aldolase A structural abnormality was found in isoelectric focusing, heat stabilization, electrophoresis or enzyme kinetics.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] It was concluded that either disordered regulation or a basic defect creating more rapid tetrameric inactivation were the most probable causes.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] The first recorded case of Aldolase A deficiency was described in 1973 (Beutler et al.) of a Jewish Canadian boy of Romanian descent.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] As his parents were first cousins, the presentation of dysmorphic features is conjecturally linked to confounding homozygosity at additional recessive loci.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] Inborn errors of metabolism are not typically associated with malformation and subsequent cases have lacked such physical manifestations.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] In particular this leads to a complication for clearly delineating the effects of enzymatic aldolase-A deficiency.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] The two familial male patients reported in 1981 (having been born in 1967 and 1979) were from a small Japanese island indicating a similar possibility of consanguinity.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] However, unlike in the primary instance parental aldolase activity was also partially reduced without significant physiological ailment.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] The other two cases documented in 1996 and 2004 lacked evidence for contiguity and deviated from previous findings in demonstration of additional myopathic complaints.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] The former boy's parents' and brother's aldolase activity's were half that of normal control values.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] The Sicilian girl's mother had benign hereditary elliptocytosis, a dominant condition resulting in elongated erythrocytes, which was passed on to her.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/aldolase-a-deficiency] However, her father's blood count and smear produced normal findings.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] It should not be confused with cyclic AMP-activated protein kinase (protein kinase A).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK is a heterotrimeric protein complex that is formed by α, β, and γ subunits.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Each of these three subunits takes on a specific role in both the stability and activity of AMPK.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Specifically, the γ subunit includes four particular Cystathionine-β-synthase (CBS) domains, giving AMPK its ability to sensitively detect shifts in the AMP/ATP ratio.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK is deactivated upon AMP displacement by ATP at CBS site 3, suggesting CBS3 to be the primary allosteric regulatory site.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] The four CBS domains create two binding sites for AMP commonly referred to as Bateman domains.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Binding of one AMP to a Bateman domain cooperatively increases the binding affinity of the second AMP to the other Bateman domain.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] As AMP binds both Bateman domains the γ subunit undergoes a conformational change which exposes the catalytic domain found on the α subunit.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] It is in this catalytic domain where AMPK becomes activated when phosphorylation takes place at threonine-172 (on α1 isoform) or Thr-174 (on α2 isoform) by an upstream AMPK kinase (AMPKK).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] The α, β, and γ subunits can also be found in different isoforms: the γ subunit can exist as either the γ1, γ2 or γ3 isoform; the β subunit can exist as either the β1 or β2 isoform; and the α subunit can exist as either the α1 or α2 isoform.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Although the most common isoforms expressed in most cells are the α1, β1, and γ1 isoforms, it has been demonstrated that the α2, β2, γ2, and γ3 isoforms are also expressed in cardiac and skeletal muscle.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] The crystal structure of mammalian AMPK regulatory core domain (α C terminal, β C terminal, γ) has been solved in complex with AMP, ADP or ATP.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Due to the presence of isoforms of its components, there are 12 versions of AMPK in mammals, each of which can have different tissue localizations, and different functions under different conditions.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK is regulated allosterically and by post-translational modification, which work together.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] If residue Thr-172 of AMPK's α1-subunit (or Thr-174 of AMPK's α2-subunit) is phosphorylated, AMPK is activated around 100-fold; access to that residue by phosphatases is blocked if AMP or ADP can block access for and ATP can displace AMP and ADP.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Regulation of AMPK by CaMKK2 requires a direct interaction of these two proteins via their kinase domains.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] The interaction of CaMKK2 with AMPK only involves the α and β subunits of AMPK (AMPK γ is absent from the CaMKK2 complex), thus rendering regulation of AMPK in this context to changes in calcium levels but not AMP or ADP.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK is regulated allosterically mostly by competitive binding to the CBS sites on its γ subunit between ATP (which allows phosphatase access to Thr-172) and AMP or ADP (each of which blocks access to phosphatases).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] It thus appears that AMPK is a sensor of AMP/ATP or ADP/ATP ratios and thus cell energy level.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK undergoes a large conformational change upon ATP binding.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] A region on the α subunit known as the kinase domain (KD) dissociates from its active-state conformation and loosely associates with the γ subunit ~100Å away.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] The KD also rotates ~180° in the conformational change.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Upon KD dissociation, the active loop (AL) of the α subunit which contains the critical phosphorylated Thr residue is fully exposed to upstream phosphatases.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] This conformational change represents a plausible mechanism for AMPK modulation.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] When cellular energy states are low (high AMP/ATP or ADP/ATP levels), AMPK adopts the KD-associated conformation and AMPK is protected from dephosphorylation and remains activated.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] When cellular energy states are high, AMPK adopts the KD-displaced conformation, the AL is exposed to upstream phosphatases, and AMPK is deactivated.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] The pharmacological compounds Merck Compound 991 and Abbott A769662 bind to the allosteric drug and metabolism site (ADaM) on the β subunit and have been shown to activate AMPK up to 10-fold.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] ADaM site binding may have roles in AMPK activation as well as protection against dephosphorylation.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] There are other mechanisms by which AMPK is inhibited or activated by insulin, leptin, and diacylglycerol by inducing various other phosphorylations.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK may be inhibited or activated by various tissue-specific ubiquitinations.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] It is also regulated by several protein-protein interactions, and may either be activated or inhibited by oxidative factors; the role of oxidation in regulating AMPK was controversial as of 2016.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] When AMPK phosphorylates acetyl-CoA carboxylase 1 (ACC1) or sterol regulatory element-binding protein 1c (SREBP1c), it inhibits synthesis of fatty acids, cholesterol, and triglycerides, and activates fatty acid uptake and β-oxidation.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK stimulates glucose uptake in skeletal muscle by phosphorylating Rab-GTPase-activating protein TBC1D1, which ultimately induces fusion of GLUT4 vesicles with the plasma membrane.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK stimulates glycolysis by activating phosphorylation of 6-phosphofructo-2-kinase/fructose-2,6-bisphosphatase 2/3 and activating phosphorylation of glycogen phosphorylase, and it inhibits glycogen synthesis through inhibitory phosphorylation of glycogen synthase.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] In the liver, AMPK inhibits gluconeogenesis by inhibiting transcription factors including hepatocyte nuclear factor 4 (HNF4) and CREB regulated transcription coactivator 2 (CRTC2).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK inhibits the energy-intensive protein biosynthesis process and can also force a switch from cap-dependent translation to cap-independent translation, which requires less energy, by phosphorylation of TSC2, RPTOR, transcription initiation factor 1A.66, and eEF2K.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] When TSC2 is activated it inhibits mTORC1.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] As a result of inhibition of mTORC1 by AMPK, protein synthesis comes to a halt.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Activation of AMPK signifies low energy within the cell, so all of the energy consuming pathways like protein synthesis are inhibited, and pathways that generate energy are activated to restore appropriate energy levels in the cell.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK activates autophagy by directly and indirectly activating ULK1.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK also appears to stimulate mitochondrial biogenesis by regulating PGC-1α which in turn promotes gene transcription in mitochondria.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK also activates anti-oxidant defenses.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Additionally, recent discoveries can conceivably suggest a direct AMPK role in increasing blood supply to exercised/trained muscle cells by stimulating and stabilizing both vasculogenesis and angiogenesis.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Taken together, these adaptations most likely transpire as a result of both temporary and maintained increases in AMPK activity brought about by increases in the AMP:ATP ratio during single bouts of exercise and long-term training.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] During a single acute exercise bout, AMPK allows the contracting muscle cells to adapt to the energy challenges by increasing expression of hexokinase II, translocation of GLUT4 to the plasma membrane, for glucose uptake, and by stimulating glycolysis.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] If bouts of exercise continue through a long-term training regimen, AMPK and other signals will facilitate contracting muscle adaptations by escorting muscle cell activity to a metabolic transition resulting in a fatty-acid oxidation approach to ATP generation as opposed to a glycolytic approach.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK accomplishes this transition to the oxidative mode of metabolism by upregulating and activating oxidative enzymes such as hexokinase II, PPAR-α, PPAR-δ, PGC-1, UCP-3, cytochrome C and TFAM.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Mutations in the skeletal muscle calcium release channel (RYR1) underlies a life- threatening response to heat in patients with malignant hyperthermia susceptibility (MHS).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Upon acute exposure to heat, these mutations cause uncontrolled Ca2+ release from the sarcoplasmic reticulum, leading to sustained muscle contractures, severe hyperthermia, and sudden death.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] At basal conditions, the temperature-dependent Ca2+ leak also leads to increased energy demand and activation of energy sensing AMP kinase (AMPK) in skeletal muscle.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] The activated AMPK increases muscle metabolic activity, including glycolysis, which leads to marked elevation of circulating lactate.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK activity increases with exercise and the LKB1/MO25/STRAD complex is considered to be the major upstream AMPKK of the 5’-AMP-activated protein kinase phosphorylating the α subunit of AMPK at Thr-172.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] This fact is puzzling considering that although AMPK protein abundance has been shown to increase in skeletal tissue with endurance training, its level of activity has been shown to decrease with endurance training in both trained and untrained tissue.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Currently, the activity of AMPK immediately following a 2 hour bout of exercise of an endurance trained rat is unclear.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] It is possible that a direct link exists between the observed decrease in AMPK activity in endurance trained skeletal muscle and the apparent decrease in the AMPK response to exercise with endurance training.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Although AMPKα2 activation has been thought to be important for mitochondrial adaptations to exercise training, a recent study investigating the response to exercise training in AMPKα2 knockout mice opposes this idea.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Their study compared the response to exercise training of several proteins and enzymes in wild type and AMPKα2 knockout mice.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] And even though the knockout mice had lower basal markers of mitochondrial density (COX-1, CS, and HAD), these markers increased similarly to the wild type mice after exercise training.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] These findings are supported by another study also showing no difference in mitochondrial adaptations to exercise training between wild type and knockout mice.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] The *C. elegans* homologue of AMPK, aak-2, has been shown by Michael Ristow and colleagues to be required for extension of life span in states of glucose restriction mediating a process named mitohormesis.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] One of the effects of exercise is an increase in fatty acid metabolism, which provides more energy for the cell.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] One of the key pathways in AMPK's regulation of fatty acid oxidation is the phosphorylation and inactivation of acetyl-CoA carboxylase.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Acetyl-CoA carboxylase (ACC) converts acetyl-CoA to malonyl-CoA, an inhibitor of carnitine palmitoyltransferase 1 (CPT-1).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] CPT-1 transports fatty acids into the mitochondria for oxidation.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Inactivation of ACC, therefore, results in increased fatty acid transport and subsequent oxidation.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] It is also thought that the decrease in malonyl-CoA occurs as a result of malonyl-CoA decarboxylase (MCD), which may be regulated by AMPK.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] MCD is an antagonist to ACC, decarboxylating malonyl-CoA to acetyl-CoA, resulting in decreased malonyl-CoA and increased CPT-1 and fatty acid oxidation.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK also plays an important role in lipid metabolism in the liver.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] It has long been known that hepatic ACC has been regulated in the liver by phosphorylation.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK also phosphorylates and inactivates 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-CoA reductase (HMGCR), a key enzyme in cholesterol synthesis.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] HMGR converts 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-CoA, which is made from acetyl-CoA, into mevalonic acid, which then travels down several more metabolic steps to become cholesterol.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK, therefore, helps regulate fatty acid oxidation and cholesterol synthesis.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Insulin is a hormone which helps regulate glucose levels in the body.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] When blood glucose is high, insulin is released from the Islets of Langerhans.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Insulin, among other things, will then facilitate the uptake of glucose into cells via increased expression and translocation of glucose transporter GLUT-4.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Under conditions of exercise, however, blood sugar levels are not necessarily high, and insulin is not necessarily activated, yet muscles are still able to bring in glucose.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK seems to be responsible in part for this exercise-induced glucose uptake.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Goodyear et al. observed that with exercise, the concentration of GLUT-4 was increased in the plasma membrane, but decreased in the microsomal membranes, suggesting that exercise facilitates the translocation of vesicular GLUT-4 to the plasma membrane.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] While acute exercise increases GLUT-4 translocation, endurance training will increase the total amount of GLUT-4 protein available.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] It has been shown that both electrical contraction and AICA ribonucleotide (AICAR) treatment increase AMPK activation, glucose uptake, and GLUT-4 translocation in perfused rat hindlimb muscle, linking exercise-induced glucose uptake to AMPK.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Chronic AICAR injections, simulating some of the effects of endurance training, also increase the total amount of GLUT-4 protein in the muscle cell.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Two proteins are essential for the regulation of GLUT-4 expression at a transcriptional level – myocyte enhancer factor 2 (MEF2) and GLUT4 enhancer factor (GEF).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Mutations in the DNA binding regions for either of these proteins results in ablation of transgene GLUT-4 expression.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] These results prompted a study in 2005 which showed that AMPK directly phosphorylates GEF, but it doesn't seem to directly activate MEF2.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AICAR treatment has been shown, however, to increase transport of both proteins into the nucleus, as well as increase the binding of both to the GLUT-4 promoter region.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] There is another protein involved in carbohydrate metabolism that is worthy of mention along with GLUT-4.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] The enzyme hexokinase phosphorylates a six-carbon sugar, most notably glucose, which is the first step in glycolysis.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] When glucose is transported into the cell it is phosphorylated by hexokinase.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] This phosphorylation keeps glucose from leaving the cell, and by changing the structure of glucose through phosphorylation, it decreases the concentration of glucose molecules, maintaining a gradient for more glucose to be transported into the cell.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Hexokinase II transcription is increased in both red and white skeletal muscle upon treatment with AICAR.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] With chronic injections of AICAR, total protein content of hexokinase II increases in rat skeletal muscle.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Mitochondrial enzymes, such as cytochrome c, succinate dehydrogenase, malate dehydrogenase, α-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase, and citrate synthase, increase in expression and activity in response to exercise.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AICAR stimulation of AMPK increases cytochrome c and δ-aminolevulinate synthase (ALAS), a rate-limiting enzyme involved in the production of heme.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Malate dehydrogenase and succinate dehydrogenase also increase, as well as citrate synthase activity, in rats treated with AICAR injections.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Conversely, in LKB1 knockout mice, there are decreases in cytochrome c and citrate synthase activity, even if the mice are "trained" by voluntary exercise.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK is required for increased peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor γ coactivator-1α (PGC-1α) expression in skeletal muscle in response to creatine depletion.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] PGC-1α is a transcriptional regulator for genes involved in fatty acid oxidation, gluconeogenesis, and is considered the master regulator for mitochondrial biogenesis.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] To do this, it enhances the activity of transcription factors like nuclear respiratory factor 1 (NRF-1), myocyte enhancer factor 2 (MEF2), host cell factor (HCF), and others.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] It also has a positive feedback loop, enhancing its own expression.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Both MEF2 and cAMP response element (CRE) are essential for contraction-induced PGC-1α promoter activity.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] LKB1 knockout mice show a decrease in PGC-1α, as well as mitochondrial proteins.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK and thyroid hormone regulate some similar processes.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Knowing these similarities, Winder and Hardie et al. designed an experiment to see if AMPK was influenced by thyroid hormone.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] They found that all of the subunits of AMPK were increased in skeletal muscle, especially in the soleus and red quadriceps, with thyroid hormone treatment.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] There was also an increase in phospho-ACC, a marker of AMPK activity.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Loss of AMPK has been reported to alter the sensitivity of glucose sensing cells, through poorly defined mechanisms.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Loss of the AMPKα2 subunit in pancreatic β-cells and hypothalamic neurons decreases the sensitivity of these cells to changes in extracellular glucose concentration.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Moreover, exposure of rats to recurrent bouts of insulin induced hypoglycemia/glucopenia, reduces the activation of AMPK within the hypothalamus, whilst also suppressing the counterregulatory response to hypoglycemia.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Pharmacological activation of AMPK by delivery of AMPK activating drug AICAR, directly into the hypothalamus can increase the counterregulatory response to hypoglycaemia.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] AMPK is recruited to lysosomes and regulated at the lysosomes via several systems of clinical significance.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Both of the above lysosomally localized systems controlling AMPK activate it in response to metformin, a widely prescribed anti-diabetic drug.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Some evidence indicates that AMPK may have a role in tumor suppression.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Studies have found that AMPK may exert most, or even all of, the tumor suppressing properties of liver kinase B1 (LKB1).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Additionally, studies where the AMPK activator metformin was used to treat diabetes found a correlation with a reduced risk of cancer, compared to other medications.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] In contrast, some studies have linked AMPK with a role as a tumor promoter by protecting cancer cells from stress.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Thus, once cancerous cells have formed in an organism, AMPK may swap from protecting against cancer to protecting the cancer itself.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Studies have found that tumor cells with AMPK knockout are more susceptible to death by glucose starvation or extracellular matrix detachment, which may indicate AMPK has a role in preventing these two outcomes.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] A recent study on pancreatic cancer suggests that AMPKα may play a role in the metastatic cascade and the phenotype of cancer cells.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Mechanistically, the authors propose that in the absence of AMPKα, pancreatic cancer cells are more vulnerable to oxidative stress, supporting a tumor-promoting function of AMPKα.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] A seemingly paradoxical role of AMPK occurs when we take a closer look at the energy-sensing enzyme in relation to exercise and long-term training.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Conversely, the study did not observe the same results in white quadriceps (WQ) and soleus (SOL) muscles that they did in RQ.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] The trained rats used for that endurance study ran on treadmills 5 days/wk in two 1-h sessions, morning and afternoon.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] The rats were also running up to 31m/min (grade 15%).
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Finally, following training, the rats were sacrificed either at rest or following 10 minutes of exercise.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Because the AMPK response to exercise decreases with increased training duration, many questions arise that would challenge the AMPK role with respect to biochemical adaptations to exercise and endurance training.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] This is due in part to the marked increases in the mitochondrial biogenesis, upregulation of GLUT-4, UCP-3, Hexokinase II along with other metabolic and mitochondrial enzymes despite decreases in AMPK activity with training.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] Questions also arise because skeletal muscle cells which express these decreases in AMPK activity in response to endurance training also seem to be maintaining an oxidative dependent approach to metabolism, which is likewise thought to be regulated to some extent by AMPK activity.
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] If the AMPK response to exercise is responsible in part for biochemical adaptations to training, how then can these adaptations to training be maintained if the AMPK response to exercise is being attenuated with training?
[src:aldolase-a-deficiency/amp-activated-protein-kinase] In other words, due to previous adaptations to training, AMPK will not be activated, and further adaptation will not occur, until the intracellular ATP levels become depleted from an even higher intensity energy challenge than prior to those previous adaptations.
